values:
&quot;If it was just, if it was just the two of us,&quot; she said.
&quot;What do you mean?&quot;
&quot;if it was just the two of us, tomorrow, with no itinerary and and no obligations, you know what I'd do?&quot;
&quot;Go on.&quot;
&quot;We'd go swimming in the morning, like I used to do on the last day of &nbsp;a family vacation. I'd get up early,maybe &nbsp;even skip breakfast, and go down to the pool - you know, that slightly grungy outdoor pool that came with every anonymous motel - and go for a swim and try to stretch out every possible moment until check-out time, just to make it seem like that last day was a whole day of vacation, and not a whole day of driving back to where school would start on Monday, with the plaid skirts and the grey cardigans and all that boring routine. It was worth it, even the part about having to take my soggy swimsuit in the car, because it smelled of chlorine and sunshine.&quot;
&nbsp;

One of the not-so-great things in life:

Looking at the phone and thinking, ``I can turn this off.``, then realizing, no, you promised to leave it on, in case of any news, good or bad.

Sorry!&nbsp;

Once I moved to Canada, I felt that I wanted to spend the rest of my life here. Now that I am sorting out what the rest of my life looks like, I am not so sure. I have spent most of my life here, and that fact isn't going to change. It is quite possible that I will spend &nbsp;part of the bookends of my life in the United States, which is not exactly the place where I was born.

I adore Canada, but have a love-hate relationship with the climate. I love the US too - the country, but pretty much have a hate-hate relationship with the politics. It does take some pondering, and I find myself more and more mentally straddling the divide. Where to live and how?&nbsp;
There are probably some perfect places to live, certain times of the year, and August in Vancouver is my favourite state of being.&nbsp;
